Here is my pre-workout mobility routine that I had posted on my story a couple of weeks ago. A bunch of you guys wanted me to make it a permanent post so that you can refer to it in the future so here you go!
-
I am not a mobility expert by any means. As you can see, I don’t actually know the names of any of these movements. As I got older, I noticed I that I needed to warm up more and more prior to my workouts to feel ready and started incorporating some movements that I found helpful. I’m not trying to be a yoga expert. I’m just trying to loosen myself up to avoid injury and this has certainly helped me with that.
-
Feel free to give some of these a shot as well as others that you find work well for you. Depending on the areas that are tight for you, there may be some other exercises you want to include. Conversely, you may be able to skip some of the ones I do if you don’t find it helpful for you.
-
If you are struggling with 𝐜𝐚𝐥𝐜𝐮𝐥𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐧𝐠 your 𝐦𝐚𝐜𝐫𝐨𝐬, setting up 𝐲𝐨𝐮𝐫 𝐝𝐢𝐞𝐭, and designing an 𝐞𝐟𝐟𝐞𝐜𝐭𝐢𝐯𝐞 𝐰𝐨𝐫𝐤𝐨𝐮𝐭 𝐫𝐨𝐮𝐭𝐢𝐧𝐞, check out my 𝐞𝐛𝐨𝐨𝐤 by clicking the 𝐥𝐢𝐧𝐤 𝐢𝐧 𝐦𝐲 𝐛𝐢𝐨💪🏼.
-
If you’re interested in working with me 1 on 1 for a custom plan tailored to your goals, send me an email for more information on online coaching.

Here is my most recent pull hypertrophy workout that I posted on my story a few days ago as I was doing it. For those of you who didn’t know, I always post my workouts on my story as I do them.
-
This is my second of two pull workouts for the week. The first one is with heavier weight and fewer reps. I posted that one a couple of weeks ago. My second one is with less weight and more reps.

Today’s workout was:

Lat Pulldowns: 4 sets of 10-12
One Arm Machine Rows: 4 sets of 10
Chest Supported Tbar Rows: 3 sets of 12-15
Rear Delt Flyes: 3 sets of 12
Hammer Curls: 3 sets of 20-25

Flat Bench Press: 4 sets of 4 and 1 set of 10

Dumbbell Lateral Raises: 3 sets of 10

Calves are one of the toughest body parts to develop. Part of the reason is they are fairly dependent on your genetics (to a higher degree than most muscles in my opinion) and they also get trained incorrectly. I'd like to think I have pretty decent calves so I'll share 3 tips on what has helped me the most. Number 3 is the most crucial and is what I will discuss in this video.
-
1. Frequency: Train your calves at least 2-3 times per week with 4-8 sets each workout. You can even do calves at the end of every single workout. Your calves are used to a heavy workload since you've been walking on them your whole life. They can handle the work and you won't be overtraining them.
-
2. Form: Make sure you are actually using your calves when you do calf raises. Slow and controlled on the way down and pause for a second at the top. No bouncing or using momentum. Your calves are a small muscle and it's very easy to cheat and take the emphasis off them by letting your ego get in the way. People care about how much you bench, not how much you calf raise.
-
3. **Huge Drop Sets**: This is the single technique that has helped my calves the most. On your last set of calf raises, choose a weight you can hit for 8-12 reps. Do a drop set and on the drop set count 3 second negatives and pause for a second at the top of each rep. Go to failure and then do another drop set doing the same thing. Do 3 or 4 of these drop sets with the 3 second negatives and 1 second pause at the top with each set to failure. The set should take 2-4 minutes, your calves will be burning, and it will be the sickest pump you've ever gotten. Do this at least twice per week and your calves will grow.

node.text:
STRENGTH TRAINING & FAT LOSS by @apfau
-
I’ll often get asked by people who are trying to lose fat if they should be lifting weights. The thought process is that since their primary goal is fat loss, lifting weights is a waste of time and they should just focus on diet and cardio. That’s not the right approach and here’s a great post by @physiqonomics which lays out why.
-
First, the goal should be fat loss, not just weight loss. We want most of the weight to be fat, not muscle. If you’re relatively overweight or fairly new to training, you can actually gain some muscle while losing fat by strength training. If you already have a decent amount of lifting experience and have built some muscle then you likely won’t add new muscle while losing fat but at the very least, you should try to maintain what you have.
-
As you can see in these studies, both groups lost weight but the groups that included resistance training maintained their muscle mass or even gained some whereas the groups that did not include resistance training lost muscle.
-
Remember, the more muscle you have, the more calories your body will require to maintain its weight which makes dieting easier. You can and should also include some cardio but relying on cardio alone is a misconception. You’ll definitely want to include some weight training if your goal is to lose fat.
-

POTATOES by @apfau
-
A common misconception is that sweet potatoes are “good” and white potatoes are “bad.” I believe this started because of people’s obsession with the Glycemic Index (GI). However, research has shown that the GI of a particular food has little to do with it being “healthy” or its likelihood to be stored as fat. In fact, watermelon has a higher GI than soda.
-
Instead, what really matters for losing and gaining weight is your overall macros and calories for the day. Sweet potatoes and white potatoes both have very similar calories. They have different nutrient profiles but both contain tons of nutrients. You can eat white potatoes, sweet potatoes, both potatoes, hot potatoes, or no potatoes. It’s your choice but they’re both great carb sources. Swipe left for a helpful post by @healthmylifestyle which further compares the two. The info is based on 255g baked with skin.

T-BAR ROWS by @apfau
-
T-bar rows are a great back exercise but they seem to get overlooked. It’s probably because a lot of gyms don’t have a place to do them and they are a bit annoying to set up. I like to use either the V attachment like I am using here or a slightly wider T shaped one.
-
People try to go way too heavy on these and tend to either use a limited range of motion, momentum, or a combination of both. When you go too heavy, the weight will pull you forward which makes retracting your scapula nearly impossible.
-
Make sure to keep your feet planted to the ground with a slightly wider than shoulder width stance for stability. If you use too narrow of a foot stance, you’ll likely get pulled forward by the weight and round your back. Keep your back tight, neck neutral, retract your scapula, and row towards your bellybutton while driving the weight with your elbows.
-

FITNESS MYTHS by @apfau
-
When it comes to fitness myths, it seems like there is a never ending list. Here are three common ones.
-
First, sweating does not burn additional calories and does not indicate whether or not your workout is effective. It might indicate that you’re working hard but it could also just mean the gym is hot or you sweat easily. If you’re trying to determine whether you’re making progress, you should focus on whether your strength is increasing if it’s a lifting related goal or if your endurance is improving if it’s a cardio related goal.
-
Second, the anabolic window, which refers to the window of time after your workout in which you must consume your post workout meal, is severely exaggerated. If you had a decent pre-workout meal, your body will still be digesting the amino acids and other nutrients once your workout is finished so there really is no need to rush. If you trained fasted, I would try to eat within an hour. Otherwise, hitting your overall macros at the end of the day is what actually matters. I wouldn’t intentionally delay eating your post workout meal and would suggest having it as soon as reasonably possible but there’s no need to shove a protein shake down your throat in the gym bathroom.
-
Lastly, muscle soreness is typically caused by training the muscles in a way they are not used to. As you perform an exercise more often, you will experience less soreness. That’s why you get extremely sore when you come back to the gym after some time off or when you try a new exercise. If soreness was really such a strong indication of workout effectiveness, you’d be better off only training every other week so that you’d get very sore every time but I’m pretty sure all of you would agree that taking every other week off wouldn’t be the smartest idea.

PICK YOUR SPLIT by @apfau
-
One of the most popular questions I get asked is how many days you should work out per week. My answer is usually something like “it depends on a bunch of factors.” It’s not about how many days you spend in the gym but what you do with your time in the gym.
-
As a beginner, I recommend a 3 day full body routine. Full body routines can also be useful for people with limited time to work out during the week since you can train each body part multiple times per week while only spending a total of 3 days in the gym.
-
As an intermediate and advanced lifter, I recommend either a 4 day or 5 day routine. It really comes down to your schedule and personal preference. I personally have done the 4 day routine for the majority of the time I’ve been lifting because I enjoyed it the most and didn’t want to be in the gym more than that. You could do a 6 day push/pull/legs routine as well if you’re relatively advanced and really love training.
-
Ultimately, all of these routines have one major thing in common. They train each muscle multiple times per week. Beyond that, any of these routines will get you what you put into it. If you’re focusing on compound lifts, progressive overload, training with intensity, and have your diet/recovery on point, you will make progress. Most importantly, you should be realistic and choose a routine that you will be able to stick to and enjoy. I rather see someone consistently stick to a 3 day routine than try to follow a 4-5 day routine but skip workouts every week.

CUTTING ON A BUDGET by @apfau
-
Following up my recent bulking on a budget post, here is cutting on a budget. Now, I want to be clear that there is no such thing as a “fat loss” food or a “muscle building” food. Any food can be eaten whether you are trying to gain muscle or lose fat. Whether you are in a caloric surplus or deficit will determine if you’re gaining or losing weight. However, there are certainly foods that are more cut “friendly” since these foods are typically lower calorie and higher volume so that you can do your best to manage hunger even while eating in a caloric deficit. These are some “cut friendly” foods that are relatively inexpensive.
-
Carbs are usually the least expensive while protein is the most expensive. Frozen veggies are cheap, filling, and easy to prepare. Potatoes and oats are both pretty cheap, especially if you buy in bulk, and are two of the most filling carb sources. Fruits like apples and melons are also lower calorie and filling as compared with bananas which are inexpensive but are also a much higher calorie fruit.
-
The price range of chicken breast can vary quite a bit but if you’re willing to look for deals, buy in bulk, and freeze it, you can certainly get a good deal. Additionally, chicken breast is one of the leanest sources of protein. Eggs are always inexpensive and are not only a good protein source but fat source as well. You can wait for a sale on whey protein that can last for months. For fats, buying nuts in larger quantities is usually the most affordable and can last a long time. Cutting is usually less expensive than bulking simply because less food is required.

2011 CUTTING PROGRESS by @apfau
-
Here is some of my cutting progress over the course of 3 months during my contest prep back in 2011. As you can see, I’ve never mastered the skill of flexing as hard as possible and not looking like constipated frog. It’s harder than it looks. Give it a shot.
-
This is a clear example of slow, steady fat loss and the huge difference it makes in your physique. I probably have the most amount of muscle in picture 1. However, with the illusion of being leaner, I look bigger in picture number 6.
-
From start to finish, I ended up losing over 30 pounds. I started at 193 pounds and ended around 160 pounds after the last photo here. I didn’t do anything fancy. I was just extremely consistent and obsessive to an extreme. I aimed to lose no more than 1-2 pounds per week. I tracked my macros, trained hard, and did a lot of cardio, especially towards the end. I didn’t have any slip ups and kept this up for over 4 months. I didn’t avoid any specific foods. I didn’t do fasted cardio. I didn’t take a fat burner. The process of losing fat is not a difficult one. The discipline it takes to execute that process is the challenge.

CARDIO CALORIES by @apfau
-
What’s your favorite form of cardio? I don’t think I have one. I dislike all forms of cardio relatively equally 😢. Ideally, you should choose a method of cardio that you enjoy the most or if you’re like me, dislike the least.
-
These are just rough estimates of how many calories you’ll burn in an hour of these methods of cardio. The numbers are NOT exact because there are several variables that will have in impact. The main one is intensity. Are you walking at 3 mph? 4 mph? Are you walking on an incline? Are you running at 6 mph? 9 mph? Somewhere in between? How about jump roping? How fast are you going? Is it continuous? Do you take breaks? Another important variable is your height/weight. The larger you are, the more calories you’ll burn during any of these methods.
-
However, it is helpful to at least see a rough comparison of the difference between overall calories burned among popular methods of cardio. “An hour” of cardio isn’t exactly a reliable method of measurement since depending on your cardio method of choice, it can vary pretty significantly.

DEADLIFTS by @apfau
-
Deadlifts are a complex exercise. There are many moving parts to pay attention to so you shouldn’t expect to be an expert right away. After doing them for years, I’m still always trying to tweak and improve my form.
-
However, these are some of the big ticket factors to focus on. First, the bar should start over your mid foot. You want the bar to be closest to your center of gravity. If it’s too far away, you’ll be in a weaker position and your back will probably round as well. Keep your shoulders over the bar.
-
Next, your foot stance should be slightly wider than hip width and you should grip the bar just outside your feet.
-
You don’t want to start with your hips too high since you won’t be in your strongest position and you’ll also likely round your back. On the opposite side of that, you also don’t want to keep your hips too low and “squat” the weight up or you’ll be wasting energy at the bottom of the lift.
-
You should make sure you nail your form down before you start increasing the weight. Deadlifts are an awesome exercise but can also be the most dangerous if you use bad form and go too heavy.
